body: "# Story — Beyond-PM domains on pm SDK primitives\n\nAs a **platform developer**, I can model a **non-PM domain system** — for example a git-like version-control workflow (changesets, refs, merges) or a company's business processes (approvals, invoicing, HR flows) — using **only public pm SDK primitives**, so the SDK proves itself as a universal, event-sourced application platform rather than a PM-only toolkit.\n\n## Why\nThe product vision (ADR pm-oxq5) states the SDK should be extensible enough to build \"an entire SCV like Git or entire companies and their business logic\". Today every SDK story/exemplar (pm-w89s, pm-cbwg) stays inside the PM domain. Nothing exercises — or even inventories — the primitive set a foreign domain needs: fully custom item types and status graphs, domain verbs via extension commands, transactional multi-item mutations, event-sourced history replay as domain state, and hooks as business rules.\n\n## Scope (exploration story, horizon 5)\n- Inventory the primitive gaps: which SDK capabilities does a non-PM domain need that the promoted primitive set (pm-rjqr/pm-98cz/pm-3mna/pm-4a7m et al.) does not yet expose?\n- Feed each gap back as a concrete SDK item under pm-usfg (create-only, dedupe-checked).\n- Acceptance is demonstrated by the exemplar spike child, not by shipping a production VCS.\n\n## Out of scope\nBuilding a real VCS or ERP; performance parity with git; any core storage change (scale work belongs to pm-9rxu).\n\n## Sequencing\nAfter the PM-domain exemplar pm-cbwg proves the custom-PM-tool story, and after the schema/config SDK promotion pm-3mna. Parked at P4 with pm-is1a (federation) in horizon 5."
